fields.name: Botanica Exotica
fields.description: Taking inspiration from Elizabeth Blackwell's "A Curious Herbal, Containing Five Hundred Cuts of the Most Useful Plants, Which Are Now Used in the Practice of Physick," published in 1739, this series modernizes her plant illustrations, drawn from London's Chelsea Physik Garden. The original collection was received favorably, and funded the release of her husband from debtors' prison.

fields.name: Baby Monsters
fields.description: Let us introduce you to the Baby Monsters Series, new to HotButteredGrits.com. How do these huge personalities fit into such small bodies? Unlike other mythological creatures, they are never ill-mannered or mischievious. Sure, they'll play a joke now and then... but it's always in good fun and never mean-spirited. They love to dance and sing, and tend to live outside of human sight. Fun, playful, and usually a bit confused, these creatures are curious but frighten easily.

fields.name: Historiae Naturalis
fields.description:
The Historiae naturalis was published in London between 1650 and 1653 by Joannes Jonstonus and Georg Marggraf with illustrations by Matthaeus Merian. It is a collection of creatures, broken out into a series of six books (the translation below from the Latin is approximate).

  • Libri 1: Historiae naturalis de quadripedibus (The Natural History Book of the Four-Legged Animal).
  • Libri 2: Historiae naturalis de serpentibus (The Natural History Book of the Serpent).
  • Libri 3: Historiae naturalis de insectis (The Natural History Book of Insects).
  • Libri 4: Historiae naturalis de exanguibus aquaticis (The Natural History book of the Bloodless Waters).
  • Libri 5: Historiae naturalis cetis et de piscibus (The Natural History Book of Fish and Whales).
  • Libri 6: Historiae Naturalis de avibus (The Natural History Book of Birds).

From the 16th and into the 19th centuries, European books – especially those of scientific, literary or other "academic" purpose – were commonly authored in Neo-Latin. This afforded knowledge to be shared amongst the learned elite throughout Europe, regardless of the local language.
